{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/make-a-beautiful-scatterplot-in-in-a-few-lines-in-python-to-make-your-report-outstanding-f47db0532094", "time": 1683008939.786228, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/make-a-beautiful-scatterplot-in-in-a-few-lines-in-python-to-make-your-report-outstanding-f47db0532094/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Make a beautiful scatterplot in a few lines in Python to make your report outstanding | by Di(Candice) Han | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Make a beautiful scatterplot in a few lines in Python to make your report outstanding", "description": "Everyone knows what scatter plots look like \u2014 several dots scattered in a plane having horizontal and vertical axes. Scatter plots are useful data visualization tools for illustrating a trend. The\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Everyone knows what scatter plots look like \u2014 several dots scattered in a plane having horizontal and vertical axes. Scatter plots are useful data visualization tools for illustrating a trend.", "The scatter plot I am going to introduce in this tutorial is more attractive than the normal one. It is dynamic with ripple effects of each dot and a slide bar which you can slide to filter the data. Below chart is what we are going to make. To create this chart, you just need a few lines of Python codes.", "Before you write these few lines of codes, you need to install the visualization package called Pyechart. It is a Python echarts plotting library. It provides more than 30 kinds of charts. The latest version is 1.7.1 and it was released on March 12th 2020. You can pip install it.", "After the library is installed, we can start to build the beautiful bar chart:", "With just three lines of codes you will get a chart like this,", "You can add another series of data to compare the revenue performance of two companies. I am going to add another e-commerce company- Alibaba.", "Pyechart libary provides many kinds of shapes, such as \u2018circle\u2019, \u2018rect\u2019, \u2018roundRect\u2019, \u2018triangle\u2019,\u2019diamond\u2019, \u2018pin\u2019, \u2018arrow\u2019, and \u2018none\u2019. You need to use uppercase to pass those values to the parameter, for example, SymbolType.DIAMOND.", "Now let us add the title and subtitle to complete the chart.", "We can further beautify the chart and make the chart more interactive. We will add a slide bar.", "To add the slide bar, we need to add the opts.VisualMapopts function inside the global option settings.", "pos_left is to define the location of the sliding bar.", "type is to define the type of sliding bar, either \u2018color\u2019 or \u2018size\u2019.", "max_ and min_ to limit the maximum and minimum values of the sliding bar.", "pos_bottom is used to define the distance to the bottom.", "Pyechart provides options to beautify labels and ripple effects.", "With label options, you can define the position, font, size, weight, color, alignment, etc.", "With effect options, you can change the brush type, color, symbol, symbol size etc to get the animation effect you would expect.", "I added some parameters to the label and effect options as below.", "You will have an even more eye-catching chart.", "There are numerous options and parameters you can explore and try out to beautify your charts even more.", "If you are interested in making other types of beautiful charts, you may want to check out my other posts.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Senior Data Analyst, passionate about telling stories with data, strong at applying data mining, modeling and visualization skills to solve real problems"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ff47db0532094&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signi